_Methodology development and preclinical safety and efficacy testing of mutation-corrected autologous midbrain dopaminergic progenitor cells for the treatment of familial Parkinson’s disease_

\

_Background_

Background
Parkinson’s disease is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder characterized by the progressive loss of dopaminergic neurons from the substantia nigra, resulting in debilitating motor and non-motor symptoms. Current standard-of-care therapies include dopamine replacement and deep brain stimulation. While these interventions can provide symptomatic relief, they do not affect the underlying disease progression; moreover, their efficacy wanes over time, and patients often develop complications such as motor fluctuations and dyskinesias. There remains a critical and urgent need for disease-modifying interventions that halt the ongoing loss of dopaminergic neurons, especially as the prevalence of Parkinson’s disease continues to rise.

Cell replacement therapy is one such emerging approach. In contrast to that of more diffuse neurodegenerative diseases, the disease pathology in Parkinson’s is relatively precisely anatomically and cellularly defined, allowing a clear target for restoration. Current ongoing clinical trials use either allogeneic human embryonic stem cells (hESCs) or autologous human induced pluripotent stem cells (hiPSCs) generate surgically transplanted cell products that can engraft, mature, and functionally integrate to replace lost cells. This includes my lab’s ongoing clinical trial using autologously derived midbrain dopaminergic precursor (mDAP) cells, which capitalizes on Shinya Yamanaka’s groundbreaking discovery that human somatic cells can be reprogrammed into ESC-like iPSCs. hiPSCs not only avoid ethical concerns associated with hESCs but also enable the generation of a cell product that can be reliably obtained and extensively tested for safety and efficacy. The use of autologous (i.e., patient-derived) cells avoids the need for immunosuppression and prolonged prophylactic use of antibiotics, a source of significant risk in allogeneic clinical trials, allowing the possibility of truly personalized precision medicine.

However, no ongoing trial has specifically addressed the risk that transplanted cells will be lost to the same degenerative process underlying disease progression. As many as 15-20% of Parkinson’s patients have an inherited or genetic form of the disease, and this number is likely to rise as the genetic drivers of Parkinson’s disease risk become better understood. This proportion is even larger in early- and young-onset patients, who typically also face more severe symptoms and progression. The application of cell replacement therapy to familial Parkinson’s patients with a younger age-of-onset is therefore complicated not only by a longer risk window for immuno-rejection, in the case of hESC-derived therapies, but also that patient-derived transplanted tissue will be subject to the same pathogenic cellular dysfunction, in the case of autologous hiPSC-derived therapies.


